    slug: "islamic-etiquettes-for-newborn-child",
    description: `Islamic Etiquettes for Newborn Child is a comprehensive guide that consolidates the Islamic teachings and rulings related to the period surrounding the birth of a child, covering the religious obligations, recommended practices, and supplications that Muslim parents should observe from the moment of birth through the early days and weeks of a newborn's life. The book draws upon authentic hadith narrations and the established rulings of Islamic jurisprudence (fiqh) to provide clear, practical guidance on every aspect of welcoming a new child into the Muslim community. The text begins with a discussion of the Islamic perspective on childbirth and the blessings that a newborn represents, establishing the spiritual context that frames all the practices that follow. It then proceeds to detail the specific actions that are recommended or obligatory when a child is born. These include the adhan (call to prayer) being whispered into the newborn's right ear and the iqamah into the left ear immediately after birth, a practice established by the Prophet Muhammad (peace be upon him) that symbolises the child's entrance into the community of Muslims. The book explains the significance of the tahneek, the practice of rubbing a softened date or something sweet on the newborn's palate, and discusses who is best suited to perform this act. The naming of the child is addressed in detail, with guidance on choosing good Islamic names, the prohibition of certain names, and the importance of selecting names that reflect the child's Muslim identity. The practice of aqiqah, the sacrifice of an animal on behalf of the newborn, is explained with its specific conditions, timing, and the recommended distribution of the meat. The book also covers the shaving of the newborn's head on the seventh day, the giving of sadaqah (charity) equivalent to the weight of the shaved hair in silver, and the circumcision of male children. Supplications for the protection and well-being of the newborn are provided throughout, drawing from authentic sources. The author addresses contemporary questions that modern Muslim parents may have, making this book a practical and relevant resource for families welcoming a new child. Written in clear and accessible language, this guide is indispensable for expectant and new parents, Islamic educators, and anyone involved in providing counsel to Muslim families.`,
    metaDescription: "Islamic Etiquettes for Newborn Child offers authentic guidance on adhan, aqiqah, naming, and other Islamic practices for welcoming a newborn."
